<div id="review_1399151492" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1399151492" />
    <a title="Sundar Raj" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9796424-sundar-raj"><img alt="Sundar Raj" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1400086182p2/9796424.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1399151492?book_show_action=true">Sep 23, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sundar Raj" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sundar Raj" href="/user/show/9796424-sundar-raj">Sundar Raj</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1399151492" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15476161257848798231">As a human beings, we have choice to accept or reject truth based on evidence. Or you can always choose denial. That seems to be the order of things in Sri lanka. The truth here being the abject failure of the state to protect its citizens,the tigers were never the saviors of the tamil cause. <br/> The atrocities of the tigers were as bad as the government&apos;s atrocities today. They have killed innocent people as much as the army. Their bigot power structure and force recruitment of young innocent yout</span>
  <span id="freeText15476161257848798231" style="display:none">As a human beings, we have choice to accept or reject truth based on evidence. Or you can always choose denial. That seems to be the order of things in Sri lanka. The truth here being the abject failure of the state to protect its citizens,the tigers were never the saviors of the tamil cause. <br /> The atrocities of the tigers were as bad as the government's atrocities today. They have killed innocent people as much as the army. Their bigot power structure and force recruitment of young innocent youths were outrageous. They were intolerant towards tamils of different religion to a point that they killed many of them. Going by their own logic, why wouldn't Sinhalese people want to do that too?. The tamil cause had a meaning and significance. Now, there is no way for tamils to even to pass of as a second class citizens in their own country. Many people seeking asylum in other countries and people who are left in the island live in a constant state of fear. What has this war achieved?. The tigers were to be strongly blamed for this because they were also not interested in a peaceful solution. <br /> Srilankan government which seems to be in a delusional state and they actually think that they can erase what happened if they denied all the charges. You cannot go 'oops,sorry, that happened,lets just forget all about it and move on as a "one nation" ' after killing thousands of innocent civilians. The terrifying accounts of the end war will haunt sri lanka's soul forever. There are videos and documentaries that will melt even strongest of us. Even though UN is taking some actions on what happend during the endwar. It is not necessary for outsiders to tell sri lanka what to do. If they don't accept there had been grave mistakes, it is ultimately them that are going to suffer.If there is no acceptance,there is no healing. <br /><br />Coming to the book, samanth has done an excellent job of being fair to all the sides. The book is well researched and presents facts rather than taking sides. The narrative was gripping and stories flow smoothly as possible. This book stands out in a way that it presents how the war has changed cultural,economical and social landscape of the country instead of just presenting painful war memories. It is not just the accounts of just tamils who suffered. There were many good Sinhalese people who batted for peace and attacked the government who were either silence or killed(but as the book points out, they just go missing indefinitely after being nabbed by a unmarked white van).<br /><br />I am eagerly waiting for the author's next book. <br /><br /><br /><br /> <br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="15476161257848798231" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


