    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1225992930" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1225992930" />
    <a title="Sankara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7963414-sankara"><img alt="Sankara" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1330434979p2/7963414.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1225992930?book_show_action=true">Mar 12, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sankara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sankara" href="/user/show/7963414-sankara">Sankara</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7963414-sankara?shelf=india-society">india-society</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1225992930" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14892083342669122539">The book is very absorbing. The narrative is mostly made up of personal, real life stories of people affected by the war. It is based on intensive field work and research which the author has undertaken, traveling to almost all parts of Sri Lanka and staying there for good length of time. The stories from all the affected sides are told - Tamils, Muslims and also the Sinhalese critics of the govt. It gives a feeling that every community is a victim in this island, with the State waging a bloody </span>
  <span id="freeText14892083342669122539" style="display:none">The book is very absorbing. The narrative is mostly made up of personal, real life stories of people affected by the war. It is based on intensive field work and research which the author has undertaken, traveling to almost all parts of Sri Lanka and staying there for good length of time. The stories from all the affected sides are told - Tamils, Muslims and also the Sinhalese critics of the govt. It gives a feeling that every community is a victim in this island, with the State waging a bloody war against a section of its own citizens. There are heart rending stories of two women, a Tamil and a Sinhalese, searching for their "missing" husbands, one a surrendered Ex Tiger, taken into Army's custody during war, and the other a journalist who suddenly disappeared one day.. There are stories from a variety of people - ex Army officers, war widows, highly politicized Buddhist monks, journalists, social workers and also migrated Tamil families living in Canda and UK.<br /><br />This book is by no means an exhaustive account of the Sri Lankan problem or the civil war, but it gives haunting glimpses of the lives of people, some shattered, some sustained, some just going on in the highly divided Island of Sri Lanka, still bleeding with many open wounds, unhealed. It is essentially a cross sectional look at the present Sri Lanka, also offering the context and historical perspectives of the conflict - like the narrative on the epic Mahavamsha, the legends of exploits of Sinhala king Dutegamanu, background of LTTE's birth and its early days etc. There are notable exceptions not at all touched by the book - like IPKF saga or internal divisions among Tamil communities. Nevertheless, on the aspects that are covered, the book gives an unbiased and insightful viewpoint. The discerning reader can spot the deep sense of empathy towards the victims, particularly the innocent Tamils of the Island, running as an unbroken thread all though the book.<br /><br />Because of author's journalist background, it reads like a travelogue, diary or report at some places, but the writer in him also comes alive and shines brilliantly, making the book eminently readable.<br /><br />It has also been translated in Tamil as இலங்கை: பிளந்து கிடக்கும் தீவு, published by கிழக்கு பதிப்பகம். </span>
  <a data-text-id="14892083342669122539" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


